<!-- begin page content -->
<div style="padding:5px 10px 0px 10px;">
<h1>
	2011&ndash;2012&nbsp; Dartmouth Computer Science Colloquium Schedule</h1>
<p>
	All colloquia take place on Wednesday at 4:15 in <strong>006 Steele</strong> unless otherwise noted.</p>
<hr />
<h2>
	May 16:<br />
	Nicole <span data-scayt_word="Immorlica" data-scaytid="1">Immorlica</span>, Northwestern University</h2>
<h3>
	Optimal Auctions over Social Networks</h3>
<p>
	We consider the problem of selling a digital good, like a Facebook App, in a social network. &nbsp;We focus on goods that exhibit &quot;tennis racket externalities&quot; -- i.e., goods that have value only when used in conjunction with other users. &nbsp;In a social network, this means that the digital good has no value to a user unless at least one of his friends in the network also owns the good. &nbsp;This severely complicates the problem of selling the digital good as a user&#39;s value, and hence the price we can charge, depends not only on his own situation, but on the situation of his friends as well. &nbsp;In this talk, we develop auctions for selling such goods in a social network. &nbsp;Our auctions provably extract a constant fraction of the optimal revenue.</p>
<p>
	Joint work with N. <span data-scayt_word="Haghpanah" data-scaytid="3">Haghpanah</span>, V. <span data-scayt_word="Mirrokni" data-scaytid="4">Mirrokni</span>, and K. <span data-scayt_word="Munagala" data-scaytid="5">Munagala</span>.</p>
<p>
	<strong>Bio:</strong><br />
	Nicole <span data-scayt_word="Immorlica" data-scaytid="2">Immorlica</span> is an assistant professor of computer science at Northwestern University. &nbsp;She received her B.Sc., M.Eng., and Ph.D. from MIT in computer science. &nbsp;Her research interests include all aspects of algorithmic game theory. &nbsp;In the field of social networks, she has studied mechanism design, technology adoption, and networked <span data-scayt_word="bimatrix" data-scaytid="7">bimatrix</span> games.</p>
<hr />
<h2>
	May 9:<br />
	<span data-scayt_word="Marsette" data-scaytid="8">Marsette</span> (Marty) <span data-scayt_word="Vona" data-scaytid="9">Vona</span>, Northeastern University</h2>
<h3>
	Sensing and Perception Algorithms for Climbing and Walking</h3>
<p>
	Robots which use limbs for locomotion (vs wheels or tracks) require sensing strategies and perception algorithms that ensure each grip or foothold is reliable---the penalty for a single &quot;miss&quot; can be high. This talk covers approaches for handling both fine and coarse uncertainty in this context.</p>
<p>
	I first present two experimental studies where fine uncertainty is handled reliably with strategies of soft contact (compliance) combined with sensing of the robot&#39;s own joint deflections during contact (<span data-scayt_word="exproprioception" data-scaytid="10">exproprioception</span>). In one study a novel robot grips and climbs a vertical structure; in the other a mini-humanoid climbs a step of unknown height. In these studies a basic map of the environment resolves coarse uncertainty by expectation.</p>
<p>
	I next present dense and sparse geometric mapping algorithms for handling coarse uncertainty when a map is not available. Optical range sensors first acquire bulk <span data-scayt_word="3D" data-scaytid="11">3D</span> point samples of environment surfaces currently in view. A <span data-scayt_word="GPU" data-scaytid="12">GPU</span> algorithm integrates these to maintain a dense volumetric representation of the robot&#39;s immediate surroundings. Curved surface patches, each approximately the size of the robot&#39;s hand or foot, are then sparsely fit in that data. The volumetric representation can support collision avoidance while the patches support grip/foothold planning.</p>
<p>
	We are aiming to integrate the above approaches by matching upcoming surface patches with compliant/<span data-scayt_word="exproprioceptive" data-scaytid="13">exproprioceptive</span> strategies to contact them.</p>
<p>
	<strong>Bio:</strong><br />
	<span data-scayt_word="Marsette" data-scaytid="14">Marsette</span> <span data-scayt_word="Vona" data-scaytid="15">Vona</span> is Assistant Professor at the College of Computer and Information Science at Northeastern University. He founded the Geometric and Physical Computing group (http://ccis.neu.edu/research/<span data-scayt_word="gpc" data-scaytid="22">gpc</span>) and teaches robotics, geometric algorithms, and graphics. This talk covers work under his recently awarded NSF CAREER grant &quot;Reliable Contact Under Uncertainty: Integrating <span data-scayt_word="3D" data-scaytid="17">3D</span> Perception and Compliance.&quot; <span data-scayt_word="Vona" data-scaytid="16">Vona</span> completed his <span data-scayt_word="PhD" data-scaytid="25">PhD</span> and MS in <span data-scayt_word="EECS" data-scaytid="26">EECS</span> at MIT in 2009 and 2001. He spent 2001-2003 at NASA/<span data-scayt_word="JPL" data-scaytid="27">JPL</span> building <span data-scayt_word="3D" data-scaytid="18">3D</span> user interfaces for the Mars Exploration Rover mission (Spirit and Opportunity), for which he received the NASA Software of the Year award in 2004. He completed his BA at Dartmouth College in 1999, where he received the <span data-scayt_word="CRA" data-scaytid="28">CRA</span> Outstanding Undergraduate Researcher award for his work with Daniela <span data-scayt_word="Rus" data-scaytid="29">Rus</span> on self-reconfiguring robots.</p>
