<h2>
	April 25:<br />
	Vashek Maty&aacute;&scaron;, Harvard University and Masaryk University, Brno</h2>
<h3>
	Privacy Mechanisms for Wireless Sensor Networks &ndash; Issues and Solutions</h3>
<p>
	Wireless sensor networks come with some very challenging demands for security and privacy - they often call for protection against active attackers trying to disrupt a network operation, but also against passive attackers looking for some sensitive information like the location of a certain node or information about the movement of a tracked object. Typical countermeasures would include an intrusion detection system and a privacy mechanism. However, these often come with contradictory aims. A privacy mechanism typically tries to hide a relation between various events while an intrusion detection system tries to link the events up. This talk will present and explore some of the problems that might occur when such techniques are brought together and we also provide some ideas how these problems could be solved.</p>
<p>
	<strong>Bio:</strong><br />
	Vashek Maty&aacute;&scaron; is a Fulbright-Masaryk Visiting Scholar at the Center for Research on Computation and Society (CRCS) at Harvard University and a Professor at the Masaryk University Brno, CZ. His research interests relate to applied cryptography and security. He worked with Microsoft Research Cambridge, University College Dublin, Ubilab at UBS AG, and was a Royal Society Postdoctoral Fellow with the Cambridge University Computer Lab. Vashek edited the Computer and Communications Security Reviews, and worked on the development of Common Criteria and with ISO/IEC JTC1 SC27.</p>
<hr />
<h2>
	April 11:<br />
	Lance Williams, Nokia Research</h2>
<h3>
	Intimate Display</h3>
<p>
	The unique human interface offered by head-mounted display systems was demonstrated long ago by Ivan Sutherland. As a graduate student, I wore an experimental version at the University of Utah in 1975, and comfortably interacted with three-dimensional line drawings suspended in space. Many of the researchers involved believed this would soon be a widespread capability, with countless applications in depicting and manipulating information in visual form. It&#39;s taken much longer than we imagined. The key difficulty is designing an optical system to present images to the user at a comfortable focal depth, superimposed on the visual field. This is straightforward if size and weight are unrestricted, but to engineer a comfortable and visually inoffensive system has proved a considerable challenge.&nbsp;</p>
<p>
	For over ten years, Nokia researchers in Finland worked to develop and refine innovative diffractive optics in support of a wearable eyeglass display. Putting on a prototype, which was equipped with a gaze-tracker, was a convincing inducement to join in this development effort. At Nokia Research Center Hollywood, where my small team worked for the last three years, we designed audio affordances for an eyeglass system. Our challenge was to deliver high-quality stereo sound to the wearer without obstructing the ears, and to capture the wearer&#39;s voice in high signal quality without a visible microphone. These goals were achieved through a combination of bone-conduction transducers, near-field exploitation of multipole audio sources, and computational beam-steering of air-conduction signals.</p>
<p>
	&nbsp; This project is an example of what musician Laurie Spiegel calls, &quot;aesthetic engineering,&quot; the mutual enhancement of human technology and human arts. In this presentation, I&#39;ll briefly review past experience and contributions in this area, and offer a vision of digital media as a master bead-game and universal solvent for science, technology and the arts.</p>
<p>
	<strong>Bio:</strong><br />
	Lance Williams was introduced to computer programming by Jef Raskin, worked for Robert Haralick at the University of Kansas, and studied computer graphics and animation under Ivan Sutherland, David Evans, and Steven Coons at the University of Utah. He worked in the Computer Graphics Lab at the New York Institute of Technology (from 1976-1986) on research and commercial animation, and the development of shadow mapping and &quot;mip&quot; texture mapping. Subsequently Williams consulted for Jim Henson Associates, independently developed facial tracking for computer animation, worked for six years in Apple Computer&#39;s Advanced Technology Group and for three years at DreamWorks SKG. He completed a long-deferred Ph.D. at the University of Utah in August 2000, and received SIGGRAPH&#39;s Steven Anson Coons Award in 2001. In 2002, he received an honorary Doctorate of Fine Arts from Columbus College of Art and Design, and a motion picture Technical Academy Award. He served as Chief Scientist at Walt Disney Feature Animation before joining Applied Minds, Incorporated, in 2004, to pursue biomedical research. He worked subsequently in Google&#39;s Geo group (Maps and Earth), and most recently served as Principal Researcher at Nokia Research Center Hollywood, where he headed a small team developing audio systems for a wearable (eyeglass) display.</p>
