<h2>
	March 7:<br />
	Azarias Reda, University of Michigan</h2>
<h3>
	CS Research and the Developing World: Improving Access to Information</h3>
<p>
	Due to improvements in the buying power of individuals and the cost implications of Moore&#39;s law, access to computing and communication technologies has accelerated in developing regions. With most of the next billion internet users expected to come from emerging markets, these regions present an increasing potential for building digital services across many application domains. However, several challenges---including poor network infrastructure, user inexperience and language barriers---render many existing systems unsuitable for developing regions. My talk will present several projects towards designing appropriate systems for developing region contexts by focusing on the challenges of information access in these regions. Based on field experience in developing nations in Africa and Asia, these projects aim to understand and improve end-user experience in accessing and using digital content in challenged networks. I will first present a nuanced analysis of content access behavior for web users in developing regions, exploring behavior from logs collected at shared internet access sites, as well as usage information from a commercial social networking service with over a hundred million members worldwide. Building on these observations, I will then present two systems that were designed for improving end-user experience in information access in these regions. Finally, I will highlight some opportunities developing regions present for conducting CS research with great impact and visibility.</p>
